passages.text: Alibaba reported a solid set of results where both cloud revenues (+26% yoy, +3ppts/4ppts above GSe/V.A. consensus) and CapEx came ahead of expectations (57% higher qoq to Rmb39bn, or US\(5.4bn). China eCommerce Customer Management Revenue growth of +10% yoy came largely in- line while group adj. EBITA of Rmb39bn (- 14% yoy) came 3% ahead of GSe (yet 9% below consensus) on the back of in- line China eCommerce EBITA and significantly narrower International commerce (AIDC) losses. We note the initial positive share price reaction (+4% pre- market vs. KWEB flat) can likely be attributed to the acceleration in cloud growth (AI revenue remained at triple- digits yoy) and capex beat (higher qoq vs. peers that were mostly lower qoq due to foreign chip bans), alongside better- than- feared food delivery/Instant commerce investment drag to the June- quarter results (yet we note the investment intensity has further stepped since July).

Key highlights: 1) Taobao- Tmall CMR revenue grew healthy at 10% (in- line with GSe, vs. +12% in Mar quarter) with China E- commerce Group EBITA decrease of -21% yoy (in- line with GSe), 2) solid cloud revenue growth +26% yoy (external cloud also +26%), ahead of GSe/Visible Alpha Consensus Data of 23%/22%. Cloud margin came- in slightly lower- than- expected at 8.8% (vs. GSe of 9.3%). 3) Group non- GAAP EPADS declined 10% yoy, below GSe and Consensus Data by 7%. 4) Capital expenditure sequentially accelerated to Rmb39bn (up 2X yoy) from Rmb25bn in Mar quarter, 6) In terms of shareholder returns, the company repurchased US\(815mn in June quarter.

We expect key focus on the results call to be on: 1) AI cloud growth momentum given the ramp- up of capex (we believe could be attributed to domestic chips for inference needs, given the foreign chip restriction over the quarter), proliferation of AI inference- demand, and internal AI agent initiatives across Amap, Taobao- Tmall, and Quark; 2) Alibaba Cloud profit margin trajectory in the medium- term, with rising AI training and inference revenue contributions alongside a step- up in AI- related depreciation; 3) intensity of the latest investments (capex spend for AI, opex spend for food/instant delivery) and duration of intense food delivery subsidies, where we believe were part defensive to contain new entrances into food delivery and part offensive to tap the sizable Rmb10trn local services industry/leveraging such traffic to cross- sell to its goods offering as an

Al- driven 'everyday' app, 4) Group profit outlook in the medium- term, where we expect food delivery/instant shopping's absolute loss to peak in the Sep quarter partly offset by narrower int'l eCom losses; 5) eCommerce competitive landscape and implications for Taobao- Tmall take rate outlook, especially from Sep 2025, after a full year anniversary of a software service fee that was introduced in Sep 2024; 6) Strategic balance between shareholder return and Al/on- demand retail investments.
We are Buy- rated on BABA/9988. HK, with valuation at US\(147/HK\)142 based on SOTP. Key risks: Slower GMV growth, lower monetization, more intense competition.

Alibaba International Digital Commerce Group: revenue came in at Rmb34.7bn, \(+19\%\) yoy (in- line with GSe), amongst which, International retail/International wholesale revenues grew by \(+20\% / + 13\%\) yoy. Adj. EBITA loss came in at - Rmb59mn (from - Rmb3.6bn in 4QFY25), driven by significant improvement in AliExpress's operating efficiency and enhanced efficiency across Lazada and Trendyol.

All Others: total revenue came in at Rmb58.6bn, \(- 28\%\) yoy and adj. EBITA loss came in at - Rmb1.4bn (vs. - Rmb1.1bn loss a year ago). The revenue decrease is primarily attributable to the disposal of Sun Art and Intime businesses, while partly offset by the increase in revenue from Freshippo, Alibaba Health and Amap.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
